window.docContents[135].resolve({"/Algebraic-Number-Theory/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Algebraic-Number-Theory":{"contents":"This chapter covers number fields and their rings of integers, integral bases and the\ntrace and norm forms, ideal factorisation in Dedekind domains, fractional ideals and the\nideal class group, the absolute ideal norm and the adic valuations of the height-one\nspectrum, the discriminant and its connection to the different ideal, Minkowski's bound and\nthe finiteness of the class group, Hermite's and Hermite–Minkowski's theorems, Kronecker's\ntheorem, the Dirichlet unit theorem, ramification theory and the fundamental identity,\nChevalley–Warning, and the arithmetic of cyclotomic extensions. Throughout,  denotes a\nnumber field,  its ring of integers,  its degree,\n its class group,  a prime ideal, and  the\nnumbers of real and of conjugate-pairs of complex embeddings of . Every mathlib-backed\nnode carries a (lean := …) reference naming the exact declaration, and its proof sketch\nfollows the argument that declaration actually uses, naming the lemmas the proof invokes.\nThe external nodes are informal — the source projects build against mathlib versions that\ndiffer from AINTLIB's — and each records the declaration that formalises it, an exact-source\npermalink, and whether that formalisation is sorry-free or still in progress.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean","header":"3. Algebraic Number Theory","id":"/Algebraic-Number-Theory/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Algebraic-Number-Theory"},"/Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory/Group-cohomology___-Tate-cohomology___-Herbrand-quotients___-and-local-CFT/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory--Group-cohomology___-Tate-cohomology___-Herbrand-quotients___-and-local-CFT--Local-Reciprocity-and-Local-Class-Field-Theory":{"contents":"(Local reciprocity / local class field theory.) For every finite Galois extension  of\nlocal fields () there is a canonical isomorphism\n\nthe local reciprocity map, where  is the norm. In the unramified case \nsends a uniformiser  to the arithmetic Frobenius generator () of\n, and for finite abelian , the norm subgroups order the subextensions:\n iff .\nFormalised in ClassFieldTheory: the abstract reciprocity isomorphism Rep.split.reciprocityIso is sorry-free; assembling  into a class formation (via ) and extracting the explicit map is in progress.\n\nThe reciprocity map is the specialisation of the abstract class-formation isomorphism\n() to . The two inputs that make  a\nfinite class formation are: Hilbert 90, giving ;\nand the order computation , which combines the local Herbrand quotient\n() with an inflation–restriction upper bound to pin down a generator\n of order  — the local fundamental class — constructed\nby lifting from the unramified case where it is explicit in terms of the Frobenius. Feeding the\nfundamental class into  gives . The norm-subgroup ordering is functoriality of the\nconstruction in .\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Class Field Theory and Galois Theory\u0009Group cohomology, Tate cohomology, Herbrand quotients, and local CFT","header":"4.6.5. Local Reciprocity and Local Class Field Theory","id":"/Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory/Group-cohomology___-Tate-cohomology___-Herbrand-quotients___-and-local-CFT/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Class-Field-Theory-and-Galois-Theory--Group-cohomology___-Tate-cohomology___-Herbrand-quotients___-and-local-CFT--Local-Reciprocity-and-Local-Class-Field-Theory"},"/p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces":{"contents":"This chapter covers the -adic numbers  and integers  as\nformalised in mathlib: the general language of valuations and valuative relations, the -adic\nvaluation on , , and , the -adic norm, the completion\n and its closed unit ball , completeness and compactness, the\ndiscrete-valuation-ring structure of , Hensel's lemma, Mahler's theorem on\ncontinuous functions, the -adic complex numbers  and Krasner's lemma, and the\ncharacterisation of absolute values on  by Ostrowski's theorem — together with the\nidentification of the adic completion of  at a finite place with .\nThroughout,  denotes a prime. Every mathlib node carries a (lean := …) reference naming the\nexact declaration, and its proof sketch follows the argument that declaration actually uses, naming\nthe lemmas that proof invokes.\n\nThe final part of the chapter records the theory of adic spaces proper — Huber rings, Tate rings,\nthe valuation spectrum, continuous valuations, the adic spectrum , Tate algebras,\nthe structure sheaf, perfectoid rings and spaces, Witt-vector period rings, tilting, and the\nFargues–Fontaine curve. These are formalised in the external project\nAdic-Spaces (Birkbeck), which builds against a Mathlib\nversion incompatible with the current AINTLIB build, so those nodes are informal: they carry no\n(lean := …) reference but instead a Formalised in provenance line linking to the exact source\ndeclaration and reporting its true Lean sorry-status. They connect into the dependency graph through\nthe Mathlib-backed valuation and -adic nodes of this chapter. The Adic-Spaces permalinks are\npinned to the recorded local commit fb55cd85e70cc7bf5f968b9b06197dc01d4b89fd, which is ahead of\nthe currently-published main; the links are given against that commit for exact-line provenance\neven though they may not yet resolve publicly.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean","header":"5. p-adic and Adic Spaces","id":"/p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--p-adic-and-Adic-Spaces"}});